Create Report Page 1: Dashboard - part 1 3

We are now ready to start working on our report!

Go to the "Report" page to create visualizations. Below is the finished page we want to create.

This report page we want to create an overview visual for the end user to give a good understanding of the top 10 diagnosis as well as telling a story. We want to create a clean and easy to view report so we will be formatting the visuals to enhance the user experience.

The page is divided into the following from top left going left to right:

1. Project Logo - Image

2. Project Title - Text Box

3. Navigation Box - Button and Bookmarks (explained later)

4. Text Box explaining the key values displayed to the right

5. Three Cards showcasing key values

6. Bar chart showcasing Top 10 Average Covered Charges by Diagnosis

7. Funnel showcasing Top 10 Total Discharges by Diagnosis

8. Stacked Bar Chart showcasing Top 10 Total Payment by Diagnosis

- Additional insight on medicare vs out of pocket by utilizing two colors


Before we begin, lets rename the report page to "Dashboard"

a) right click the tab and rename


Step 1. Project Logo - Image

a) Download the logo from this guide and save it on your computer.

b) Place the image on the top left corner and resize if needed.

Step 2. Project Title - Text Box

a) Add a Text Box

b) Write the text for the title

c) Format font, size and color


Step 3. Navigation Box - Button and Bookmarks (explained in later step)

Step 4. Text Box explaining the key values displayed to the right

a) Add a text box

b) Write the text as shown in the image. Highlighting the large descrepancy between the charged and payment values.

c) Format font, size and color


Step 5. Three Cards showcasing key values

a) Add a Card

b) Drag the Average Covered Charges to Fields


c) Format the card by clicking the format icon. Change the Data label color and text size

d) repeat steps for the other two cards by adding Average Total Payments and Charges Paid % to the fields.


e) To show correct value on Charges Paid %, we need to format the Measure to be %. Highlight the Charges Paid % measure and go to modeling and click the "%" icon. This will allow us to show the correct value.



Step 6. Bar chart showcasing Top 10 Average Covered Charges by Diagnosis

a) Create a Stacked Bar Chart

b) Add DRG Definition to Axis, DRG Defintion to Legend and Average Covered Charges to Value.


c) Add Top N 10 filter on DRG Defintion and add Average Covered Charges to "By value", click "Apply filter".


d) Format the bar chart.

In order to make the chart easier to read. Its best to declutter it. There are currently too many colors so lets limit the color pallet to two shades of blue. We can highlight the top 4 as they are all over 150 million in covered charges

Next, we can enhance user experience further by adding data labels. Turn on Data labels and choose position Inside End.

 

Since its easy for the user to see the actual numbers in the bars, lets remove the Y axis as well as the Legend and title.

By removing the title, we can utlize text box for better formatting options. Add a text box for a title and a text box for the summary text. Format size, font and color to match the theme.
